---
description: Write fewer, less verbose code comments — only when code isn't self-explanatory
alwaysApply: true
---

# Comment Style

Default to no comment. Only add one when the code's *why* — a non-obvious
constraint, trade-off, gotcha, or intent — genuinely can't be recovered by
reading the code itself. Never add a comment for the *what*; if a comment
would just restate the next line in English, delete it instead.

- One comment per block, not per line. Put it above the block it explains,
  not scattered through it.
- Keep it as short as the reasoning allows — a phrase or one sentence, not a
  paragraph. Only spend more words when the constraint itself is genuinely
  intricate (e.g. a cross-file gotcha), and even then trim to the minimum
  needed to convey it.
- Prefer a clearer name (variable/function) over a comment, whenever a name
  can carry the same information.
- Never narrate mechanical code (imports, simple assignments, obvious control
  flow) or restate the function/type name in prose.

```javascript
// BAD — restates the code, one comment per line, no real information
// Loop over all users
for (const user of users) {
  // Check if user is active
  if (user.active) {
    // Add to result
    result.push(user);
  }
}

// GOOD — self-explanatory, no comment needed
const activeUsers = users.filter(user => user.active);
```

```javascript
// BAD — verbose comment for a trivial retry
// This function retries the operation. It will attempt to call the
// function passed in as an argument, and if it fails, it will wait
// and then try again, up to the maximum number of retries specified.
function retry(fn, maxAttempts) { ... }

// GOOD — short, and only states the non-obvious part (why linear backoff)
// Linear backoff: this API rate-limits by fixed window, not burst, so
// exponential backoff wastes time waiting past the window reset.
function retry(fn, maxAttempts) { ... }
```
